s © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Kent): variant of   Payne  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Payne","meanings":["English: from the Middle English and Old French personal name <i>Pai(e)n</i>, <i>Pagen</i> (from Latin <i>Paganus</i>), a fairly common personal name among Normans. It derived from a word that originally meant ‘villager, rustic’, later ‘heathen’, but it had doubtless lost these connotations in its use as a late medieval personal name. This name has also been established in Ireland since the 14th century.","History: Thomas Payne, who was a freeman of Plymouth Colony in 1639, was the founder of a large American family, which included Robert Treat Paine (1731–1814), one of the signers of the Declaration of Independence. See also   Paine  ."]}]},{"name":"Ilbert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. This was the name of the founder of the only native British religious order (abolished at the Dissolution of the Monasteries),  St Gilbert  of Sempringham (  ?1083–1189 ), in whose honour it is still sometimes bestowed, especially among Roman Catholics. It gained a wider currency in the 19th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Seigneur Ilbert Payn de Montdoubleau was born in 1054, in Mondoubleau, Loir-et-Cher, Centre, France, his father, Ilbert Payen Seigneur de Montdoubleau, was 32 and his mother, Aiga de Fréteval, was 27. He had at least 4 daughters with Countess Aiga de Mondoubleau. He died in 1105, at the age of 51."},"et":{"1054–1105":"1054–1105","1045–Male":"1045–Surnud","1065–1100":"1065–1100","1085–1154":"1085–1154","1090–Female":"1090–Surnud","1091–1142":"1091–1142","1110–Female":"1110–Surnud","1022–1096":"1022–1096","1027–Female":"1027–Surnud","1091":"1091","1090":"1090","